    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-11-14T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-11-14T03:00:00-05:00" n="182"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d182">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.00/11–1446: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-11-14T10:00:00+02:00"
                            >November 14, 1946—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 11:51 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1569. See <gloss target="#t_mytel1">mytel</gloss> 1499, November 2.<note n="41"
                        xml:id="d182fn41">Not printed.</note>
                    <gloss target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss> in talk with me last evening brought
                    up question of his visiting US and I read him essential parts of <gloss
                        target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 1403 of October 30. He replied that after
                    seeing how events develop here in near future and before making final decision
                    he will again talk with me. However, he feels at present that since solution of
                    Greece’s main problems both as regards security and reconstruction depend
                    principally on decisions to be made in New York<note n="42" xml:id="d182fn42"
                        >The Third Session of the Council of Foreign Ministers met at New York City
                        from November 4 to December 12, 1946.</note> and Washington he would risk
                    important loss of prestige here <pb facs="0276" n="264" xml:id="pg_264"/> where
                    politics are so largely personal if he failed to go to US at least for brief
                    period at this critical juncture.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
